definition: where there's a start, there's a finish (idiom); to finish once one starts sth/to carry things through/I started, so I'll finish.
to have/there is/there are/to exist/to be
to have/there is/there are/to exist/to be

sentences.english: I consistently follow up on "waiting for" items.
sentences.chinese: 我總是讓“待做事項”有始有終。

sentences.english: If he begins a project, he'll go the distance.
sentences.chinese: 如果他開始一個項目，他會有始有終地完成的。

sentences.english: History teach us that every problem has a lifespan.
sentences.chinese: 每一個難題都有始有終。
堅持你已開始的，要有始有終。

sentences.english: History teaches us that every problem has a lifespan.
sentences.chinese: 歷史告訴我們，每一個難題都有始有終。

sentences.english: I like it. You proposed to me here, so it has agreeable symmetry.
sentences.chinese: 我喜歡，你在這裏向我求婚，也算有始有終。

sentences.english: Finish the work what you start, and implement it.
sentences.chinese: 做事有始有終，貫徹到底。

sentences.english: Do not stop your excellent service after the check is presented or paid.
sentences.chinese: 客人付款後也不要停止你優秀的服務，要有始有終。

sentences.english: And God will finish what He has begun.
sentences.chinese: 神作諸事向來有始有終。
